(handheld metal detector beeps)

00:34.534 --> 00:38.121
(handheld metal detector
beeping)

00:39.205 --> 00:40.123
You're clear.

00:40.206 --> 00:42.459
Thank you.

00:44.461 --> 00:45.879
{\an1}Oh. Sorry.

00:47.505 --> 00:49.424
WOMAN:
Enjoy your flight.

00:49.507 --> 00:52.469
<i>(piano playing</i>
<i>"Fly Me to the Moon")</i>

01:00.769 --> 01:01.811
{\an5}No. No, it's you.

01:00.769 --> 01:01.811
{\an1}Sorry.

01:01.895 --> 01:02.854
{\an5}It's all you.

01:01.895 --> 01:02.854
Nah, go ahead.

01:02.937 --> 01:04.480
Wait.

01:04.563 --> 01:06.316
{\an8}Justin Sanderson.

01:06.399 --> 01:07.817
Is this you?

01:07.901 --> 01:10.487
Didn't I see you
debating on TV?

01:10.570 --> 01:14.282
{\an4}Yeah.

01:10.570 --> 01:14.282
{\an3}Well, then-then,
this is yours.

01:14.365 --> 01:17.076
{\an1}Um... Okay, well, how about
in the name of civility,

01:17.160 --> 01:19.496
{\an1}I, uh, I get this
for you.

01:19.579 --> 01:21.831
{\an5}Oh, Justin, I'm honored.

01:19.579 --> 01:21.831
(chuckles): Okay.

01:21.915 --> 01:23.833
{\an3}Never met a magazine
writer before.

01:23.917 --> 01:25.710
Joe Beaumont.

01:25.794 --> 01:27.837
{\an5}Oh, uh, Justin Sanderson.

01:25.794 --> 01:27.837
{\an3}Ah.

01:27.921 --> 01:29.130
{\an3}Oh. You
wouldn't mind...

01:29.214 --> 01:31.716
Would you sign it for me?

01:31.800 --> 01:33.843
Sure. Be happy to.

01:33.927 --> 01:34.844
{\an5}To Joe.

01:33.927 --> 01:34.844
{\an1}Joe.

01:34.928 --> 01:35.845
With an "E."

01:35.929 --> 01:38.848
"Joe... with...

01:38.932 --> 01:41.518
{\an1}an 'E.'"

01:41.601 --> 01:42.519
{\an3}JOE:
Thank you.

01:42.602 --> 01:44.479
{\an5}Be seeing you.

01:42.602 --> 01:44.479
{\an1}Okay.

01:44.562 --> 01:48.358
{\an5}WOMAN (over P.A.): At this time,
Northern Gold Star Airlines

01:48.441 --> 01:50.068
{\an5}would like to invite
its Privileged Class passengers

01:50.151 --> 01:51.694
{\an5}to Flight 1015,

01:50.151 --> 01:51.694
(line ringing,
thunder rumbling softly)

01:51.778 --> 01:55.740
now departing at 10:15
to please board at Gate B15.

01:55.824 --> 01:58.326
{\an5}WOMAN (over phone):
Justin?

01:55.824 --> 01:58.326
Honey.

01:58.409 --> 02:00.703
So glad I got you
before my flight took off.

02:00.787 --> 02:02.121
{\an1}Hi.

02:02.205 --> 02:03.540
Are you okay?

02:03.623 --> 02:05.625
I am so sorry
about before.

02:05.708 --> 02:08.544
I-I really didn't mean
to raise my voice like that.

02:08.627 --> 02:10.547
{\an5}I don't think
this is a good idea.

02:10.630 --> 02:12.674
I know.
I just-- I need the work.

02:12.757 --> 02:14.592
Honey, you're not listening.

02:14.676 --> 02:16.052
You promised me.

02:16.135 --> 02:18.555
No, I know.
I-I am listening to you.

02:18.638 --> 02:20.431
And I am keeping that promise.

02:20.515 --> 02:22.600
{\an5}How?

02:20.515 --> 02:22.600
Well, because this assignment

02:22.684 --> 02:24.727
will be the opposite
of high stress.

02:24.811 --> 02:26.563
You don't know that.

02:26.646 --> 02:28.690
Because Tel Aviv
is not Yemen, hon.

02:28.773 --> 02:30.066
It's...

02:30.149 --> 02:33.069
Look. I saw some fucked-up shit,

02:33.152 --> 02:37.198
and... it shook me up.

02:37.282 --> 02:39.200
I mean, it would've
shook anyone up, but...

02:39.284 --> 02:40.827
I know, honey.

02:40.910 --> 02:44.831
{\an5}Remember what Dr. Cravat says:
the past is the past.

02:44.914 --> 02:46.749
Past is the past.

02:46.833 --> 02:49.544
And that will help me
get through the now.

02:49.627 --> 02:51.713
That's right.

02:51.796 --> 02:54.215
As will thinking about you.

02:54.299 --> 02:56.217
Okay. We're good?

02:56.301 --> 02:57.594
I love you.

02:57.677 --> 02:58.970
{\an1}JUSTIN:
Oh, one last thing.

02:59.053 --> 03:02.390
{\an1}I just noticed
my flight number is 1015,

03:02.473 --> 03:04.267
and it's October 15.

03:04.350 --> 03:08.605
And also, the departure time
was delayed from 9:30 to 10:15.

03:08.688 --> 03:10.273
What are the
odds of that?

03:10.356 --> 03:12.442
(beeping)

03:12.525 --> 03:14.068
Have a safe flight.

03:14.152 --> 03:15.278
Hi. How are you?

03:15.361 --> 03:17.989
♪ ♪

03:18.072 --> 03:19.824
(audio continues
faint and muffled)

03:26.247 --> 03:27.665
{\an1}Hey.

03:29.208 --> 03:30.919
Welcome aboard.

03:32.462 --> 03:34.213
{\an5}Good flight today?

03:32.462 --> 03:34.213
{\an1}Oh, yeah.

03:34.297 --> 03:36.174
Very good.
Welcome aboard.

03:36.257 --> 03:37.425
Thank you.

03:37.508 --> 03:39.969
FLIGHT ATTENDANT: I'm sorry,
but only an infant can travel

03:40.053 --> 03:41.262
{\an1}in a seat
with a parent.

03:41.346 --> 03:42.639
{\an1}Children two to 11
need their own seat.

03:42.722 --> 03:44.140
{\an1}I'm sure they'll discount
the fare for you.

03:44.223 --> 03:46.142
{\an3}We're only
two-thirds occupancy.

03:46.225 --> 03:47.977
{\an1}MAN: But you said
first class is full.

03:48.061 --> 03:51.189
{\an1}Yeah. I would have to move you
to the main cabin.

03:51.272 --> 03:53.483
{\an6}JUSTIN:
Excuse me.

03:51.272 --> 03:53.483
Yes, but...

03:53.566 --> 03:54.943
That's actually my seat there,

03:55.026 --> 03:57.153
{\an3}and they can have it
if they need it.

03:58.529 --> 03:59.781
{\an5}Yeah, that's fine.

03:58.529 --> 03:59.781
Yeah.

03:59.864 --> 04:00.823
Is that okay?

04:00.907 --> 04:02.325
Yeah.

04:02.408 --> 04:04.160
Thank you.
That's very nice of you.

04:04.243 --> 04:05.703
{\an3}So is there a place
I should sit?

04:05.787 --> 04:07.163
Yes. Main cabin
should be pretty thin.

04:07.246 --> 04:08.831
Uh, that side, toward the back.
Stretch out.

04:08.915 --> 04:09.916
{\an3}All right.

04:11.751 --> 04:13.419
♪ ♪

