<i>Landing at the truth this time</i>

06:55.456 --> 06:58.793
<i>will require</i>
<i>an unscheduled stopover...</i>

06:58.876 --> 07:00.878
<i>in The Twilight Zone.</i>

07:03.631 --> 07:04.799
<i>(The Twilight Zone</i> theme
playing)

07:04.882 --> 07:06.717
NARRATOR: <i> You're traveling</i>
<i>through another dimension,</i>

07:06.801 --> 07:10.346
<i>a dimension not only of</i>
<i>sight and sound but of mind.</i>

07:10.429 --> 07:13.558
<i>It is the middle ground</i>
<i>between light and shadow,</i>

07:13.641 --> 07:16.352
<i>between science</i>
<i>and superstition.</i>

07:16.435 --> 07:18.896
{\an8}<i>And it lies between</i>
<i>the pit of one's fears</i>

07:18.980 --> 07:21.732
{\an8}<i>and the summit</i>
<i>of one's knowledge.</i>

07:21.816 --> 07:24.986
<i>You are now traveling through</i>
<i>a dimension of imagination.</i>

07:25.069 --> 07:28.906
<i>You've just crossed over</i>
<i>into The Twilight Zone.</i>

07:34.078 --> 07:36.956
{\an8}RODMAN (over headphones):
Chapter two: "Ominous Signs."

07:37.039 --> 07:38.666
{\an8}There are other
aviation mysteries

07:38.749 --> 07:41.169
{\an8}we've explored on this podcast:

07:41.252 --> 07:45.089
{\an8}the crash of Transeast Airlines
Flight 22 out of Miami Beach,

07:45.173 --> 07:47.216
{\an8}or the anomaly of
Global Airlines Flight 107

07:47.300 --> 07:48.885
{\an8}out of Buffalo.

07:48.968 --> 07:51.387
{\an8}Yet what makes
Flight 1015 unique

07:51.470 --> 07:54.557
{\an8}is the number of unusual details
surrounding its disappearance,

07:54.640 --> 07:56.809
{\an8}starting with Captain Donner.

07:56.893 --> 07:59.562
{\an8}DONNER (over intercom):
We're pretty confident
of a nice, smooth flight

07:59.645 --> 08:01.397
{\an8}over the pond
and on to Tel Aviv, so...

08:01.480 --> 08:04.400
{\an8}Hey, did the pilot just say
his name was Captain Donner?

08:04.483 --> 08:06.402
{\an8}What?

08:06.485 --> 08:09.363
{\an8}Just... Never mind.

08:11.991 --> 08:13.743
{\an8}Sorry. (chuckles)

08:15.995 --> 08:19.081
{\an8}(thunder rumbling softly)

08:19.165 --> 08:22.543
{\an8}I'm sorry, this is gonna
sound very weird, uh...

08:22.627 --> 08:25.046
{\an8}but do you think you could
listen to this real quick?

08:25.129 --> 08:26.923
{\an8}Those were on your ears, bro.

08:27.006 --> 08:29.383
{\an8}Yeah. But...
this podcast,

08:29.467 --> 08:33.261
{\an9}uh, says that this flight--
like <i> this</i> flight--

08:33.346 --> 08:36.097
{\an9}is going to vanish
into the ocean.

08:36.182 --> 08:39.477
{\an9}Yeah. So, if you wouldn't mind
just listening just for a sec...

08:39.559 --> 08:41.938
{\an8}Hey, yo, I don't
want to get lice.

08:42.020 --> 08:43.188
{\an9}No, you...

08:45.650 --> 08:47.652
{\an8}Jesus. (scoffs)

09:03.876 --> 09:06.963
{\an8}RODMAN: Captain Donner noted
to air traffic control

09:07.046 --> 09:10.132
{\an8}the presence of a flock of
cormorants near Flight 1015.

09:10.216 --> 09:14.262
{\an8}In aviation circles,
a dead bird is a harbinger

09:14.345 --> 09:16.973
{\an8}of bad things to come.

09:17.056 --> 09:18.808
{\an8}Shortly after takeoff,

09:18.891 --> 09:21.477
{\an8}as the plane maneuvered
around a thunderstorm,

09:21.560 --> 09:24.355
{\an8}the flight crew reported
that a bird struck the engine

09:24.438 --> 09:25.898
{\an8}at 10:21 p.m.

09:27.358 --> 09:29.819
(panting)

09:29.902 --> 09:31.696
♪ ♪

09:36.659 --> 09:38.035
(panting)

09:39.120 --> 09:40.830
(water splashes)

09:40.913 --> 09:42.331
(panting)

09:42.415 --> 09:43.791
(quietly):
The past is past.

09:43.874 --> 09:45.334
<i>The past is past.</i>

09:45.418 --> 09:46.961
The past...

09:47.044 --> 09:48.337
<i>is past.</i>

09:48.421 --> 09:51.007
The past...

09:51.090 --> 09:53.676
is past.

09:53.759 --> 09:56.345
Past...

09:56.429 --> 09:58.097
is past.

10:09.275 --> 10:10.401
(clears throat)

10:13.112 --> 10:15.156
(electronic chime)

10:15.239 --> 10:16.615
Hi.

10:16.699 --> 10:17.908
(quietly):
One second.

10:17.992 --> 10:19.535
No, no. Please.

10:19.618 --> 10:21.037
{\an3}Please.

10:21.120 --> 10:24.540
(repeated electronic chime)

10:30.629 --> 10:32.631
{\an6}Would you?

10:30.629 --> 10:32.631
I got you, all right.

10:35.343 --> 10:37.845
Okay, uh...

10:37.928 --> 10:39.013
Yep.

10:39.096 --> 10:41.223
{\an1}Hello.
Sorry to bother you.

10:41.307 --> 10:43.059
But... (chuckles)

10:43.142 --> 10:45.394
{\an1}Um...

10:45.478 --> 10:47.396
Is that a bird out there?

10:47.480 --> 10:49.732
Uh, outside, before,
in the-the engine?

10:49.815 --> 10:51.692
Just-just now, like...

10:51.776 --> 10:53.903
Um, did we hit a bird?

10:53.986 --> 10:55.279
{\an3}Um...

10:56.530 --> 10:58.491
{\an5}I wouldn't know.

10:56.530 --> 10:58.491
{\an1}Okay.

10:58.574 --> 11:00.743
Do you think there's a way
we could maybe ask the pilot?

11:00.826 --> 11:01.535
{\an1}Um...

11:01.619 --> 11:03.245
I'd hate to trouble him
right now.

11:03.329 --> 11:05.289
Here's the thing, is that...

11:05.373 --> 11:07.291
We're still flying
and at an altitude

11:07.375 --> 11:08.751
where there are
no more birds.

11:08.834 --> 11:10.753
No more birds? Okay.

11:10.836 --> 11:12.922
{\an6}How do you know
there's no birds?

11:10.836 --> 11:12.922
{\an3}Sir?

11:13.005 --> 11:14.006
{\an3}Sir?

11:13.005 --> 11:14.006
I-I mean...

11:14.090 --> 11:15.925
{\an5}What? What?

11:14.090 --> 11:15.925
Sir, I need you
to lower your tone.

11:16.008 --> 11:18.094
{\an6}I'm not...

11:16.008 --> 11:18.094
{\an3}We'll be, we'll be
starting in-flight service

11:18.177 --> 11:19.929
{\an3}in a minute, so if you'd
like anything further,

11:20.012 --> 11:21.680
please let me know.

11:23.682 --> 11:26.268
Okay, I'll just-- I'll, um--
I'll shut up. I'm sorry.

11:26.352 --> 11:29.563
(chuckles)
I'm sorry. Thank you.

11:34.819 --> 11:37.488
(thunder rumbling softly)

11:37.571 --> 11:39.031
JOE:
It was.

11:41.033 --> 11:43.411
A bird.

11:43.494 --> 11:45.621
Real headache
coming out of Dulles.

11:45.704 --> 11:47.289
{\an1}I used to pilot
for Northern Gold Star.

11:47.373 --> 11:49.834
{\an1}They let us catch rides
on flights if there's room.

11:49.917 --> 11:51.794
{\an1}Yeah, this is
a good flight crew.

11:51.877 --> 11:53.295
{\an1}Donner, the pilot.
Nick and Tammy.

11:53.379 --> 11:54.755
I worked with them a lot.

11:54.839 --> 11:56.799
But the thing is,
they don't know.

11:56.882 --> 11:58.676
They'll never tell you
what's really going on.

11:58.759 --> 12:01.679
I don't fly anymore. One too
many mistakes I can't take back.

12:04.557 --> 12:06.475
{\an1}Yeah, that was a birdie.
(sighs)

12:06.559 --> 12:08.936
{\an1}Yeah.

12:09.019 --> 12:11.021
(thunder rumbling)

12:30.583 --> 12:32.168
(eerie music playing)

12:32.251 --> 12:36.005
{\an5}RODMAN:
So what do we really know
about Flight 1015?

12:36.088 --> 12:38.424
{\an5}We know that the last words
spoken by the pilot

12:38.507 --> 12:42.511
{\an5}to air traffic control were,
"Good night, New York."

12:42.595 --> 12:47.016
{\an5}We also know that it disappeared
at 11:15 p.m.

12:47.099 --> 12:49.018
(quietly):
I'm running out of time.

12:49.101 --> 12:51.687
{\an5}What could have happened
to cause the flight to vanish

12:51.770 --> 12:54.690
{\an5}without a trace?

12:51.770 --> 12:54.690
(electronic chime)

12:54.774 --> 12:56.192
{\an5}DONNER:
Folks, this is
the flight deck again

12:56.275 --> 12:58.986
{\an5}just to let everyone know
this storm system up ahead's

12:59.069 --> 13:01.489
{\an5}developing a little bit faster
than we anticipated.

13:01.572 --> 13:03.782
{\an5}We'll be maneuvering around it
as best we can,

13:03.866 --> 13:05.743
{\an5}but we do expect to hit
some rough patches.

13:05.826 --> 13:07.745
{\an5}Shouldn't be anything
to worry about,

13:07.828 --> 13:10.706
{\an5}but we ask you to all remain
in your seats if you can.

13:10.789 --> 13:12.541
Thank you.

13:18.923 --> 13:21.717
(thunder rumbling)

13:21.800 --> 13:26.597
{\an8}RODMAN: Chapter three:
"Every Detail Counts."

13:26.680 --> 13:30.017
{\an8}With a tragedy as enormous
as Flight 1015,

13:30.100 --> 13:33.062
{\an8}it's devastating
to think of the cost.

13:33.145 --> 13:37.066
{\an5}117 lives lost
when the pilot signed off

13:37.149 --> 13:39.068
from air traffic control

13:39.151 --> 13:43.030
{\an5}and the flight disappeared from
radar over the North Atlantic.

13:43.113 --> 13:44.406
Without any forensic evidence,

13:44.490 --> 13:46.909
{\an5}we have to start
looking for patterns,

13:46.992 --> 13:49.161
looking for clues,

13:49.245 --> 13:53.624
{\an5}small signs that could tell us
the bigger problem.

13:53.707 --> 13:57.753
{\an5}Most famous aviation mysteries
come from small beginnings:

13:57.836 --> 14:01.882
{\an5}a mechanical failure,
or fire in one of the cabins,

14:01.966 --> 14:05.427
{\an5}leading the crew to panic
and to bring the plane down.

14:05.511 --> 14:09.056
{\an5}The passengers would've looked
to the flight attendants

14:09.139 --> 14:12.893
{\an5}and known immediately
that something was wrong.

14:12.977 --> 14:15.229
{\an8}We know that the cockpit
of this particular aircraft

14:15.312 --> 14:16.814
{\an8}was equipped with cameras

14:16.897 --> 14:20.067
{\an8}that allowed the passengers
to watch the flight crew

14:20.150 --> 14:22.278
{\an8}through multiple monitors.

14:22.361 --> 14:24.238
{\an5}If the pilot were doing
something unusual,

14:24.321 --> 14:28.659
{\an5}it's likely that the whole cabin
would have noticed and reacted.

14:28.742 --> 14:32.288
{\an5}What seems more likely is
the idea that it was something

14:32.371 --> 14:34.748
truly unexpected and unique.

14:34.832 --> 14:38.210
{\an5}As the plane flew close
to a thunderstorm,

14:38.294 --> 14:40.004
{\an5}the pilot would need
to calmly communicate

14:40.087 --> 14:44.008
{\an5}with his fellow crew and keep
the flight under control.

14:44.091 --> 14:45.843
Was there something on board

14:45.926 --> 14:48.679
{\an5}that could've disrupted
the plane's communications?

14:48.762 --> 14:50.306
(quiet chatter)

14:50.389 --> 14:53.434
(sportscast playing over video)

14:56.020 --> 14:57.646
{\an1}JUSTIN:
Hi.

14:57.730 --> 15:00.316
Hello. Uh, I'm Justin.

15:00.399 --> 15:03.777
{\an1}I'm sorry, I-I know
this isn't really my business,

15:03.861 --> 15:05.988
but I just think
you may need to turn that off.

15:07.239 --> 15:08.991
Thank you for your input.

15:09.074 --> 15:11.452
{\an1}But, uh, you know
we are Sikh, right?

15:11.535 --> 15:13.621
Yeah. Absolutely.

15:13.704 --> 15:16.373
Yeah, and equal to us all. So...

15:17.416 --> 15:20.753
Okay, Justin.

15:20.836 --> 15:22.713
Then leave us all alone.

15:22.796 --> 15:25.633
Okay, I just, I feel like you do
need to turn that off, though.

15:25.716 --> 15:27.843
{\an1}It's on airplane mode.
It's on Wi-Fi.

15:27.926 --> 15:29.011
{\an6}JUSTIN: Are you gonna
turn it off or, like...?

15:27.926 --> 15:29.011
TAMMY: Mr. Sanderson?

15:29.094 --> 15:31.680
{\an4}Yes?

15:29.094 --> 15:31.680
{\an3}I'm gonna need you to go
back to your seat, please.

15:31.764 --> 15:33.390
But these guys, they're not
turning it off, so I...

15:33.474 --> 15:34.808
{\an1}Mr. Sanderson, I understand
that you're concerned.

15:34.892 --> 15:36.477
{\an1}I need you
to go back to your seat.

15:39.605 --> 15:40.522
Now.

15:40.606 --> 15:42.191
Okay.

15:42.274 --> 15:44.193
OMESH: What is he,
the cricket police?

15:44.276 --> 15:46.195
{\an3}TANVEERA:
Crazy.

15:46.278 --> 15:48.030
{\an1}TAMMY:
Guy needs to sit down.

15:50.282 --> 15:52.493
(seat belt clicks)

15:56.830 --> 15:59.708
{\an5}RODMAN:
Without any forensic evidence
to analyze,

15:59.792 --> 16:01.377
{\an5}we have to consider
other records

16:01.460 --> 16:04.380
left behind by Flight 1015.

16:04.463 --> 16:07.091
{\an5}This includes
the passenger manifest.

16:07.174 --> 16:09.093
And one infamous individual

16:09.176 --> 16:12.721
{\an5}at the front of the plane
immediately stands out:

16:12.805 --> 16:16.225
Russian citizen Igor Orlov.

16:16.308 --> 16:18.894
Igor was in witness protection

16:18.977 --> 16:22.106
{\an5}and was taking Flight 1015
to Tel Aviv

16:22.189 --> 16:25.943
{\an5}in order to testify
against the Russian mafia.

16:26.026 --> 16:29.029
{\an5}We know the Russian mob would do
anything in their power

16:29.113 --> 16:31.532
{\an5}to prevent Orlov
from testifying.

16:31.615 --> 16:34.868
{\an5}Is it possible that
they targeted Flight 1015

16:34.952 --> 16:36.954
in order to kill him?

16:39.039 --> 16:42.126
{\an5}Another detail
might fill in the picture.

16:42.209 --> 16:46.588
{\an5}Also listed on the passenger
manifest is a U.S. air marshal.

16:46.672 --> 16:50.718
{\an5}Was he on board the flight
in order to protect Igor Orlov?

16:50.801 --> 16:54.972
{\an5}Would he be able to tell us
of any threats to the aircraft?

16:57.891 --> 16:59.643
Excuse me.

16:59.727 --> 17:02.020
{\an5}Hi.

16:59.727 --> 17:02.020
I am very sorry

17:02.104 --> 17:04.522
about everything
from before, but, um...

17:06.358 --> 17:09.153
{\an1}...I really need to talk
to the air marshal.

17:09.236 --> 17:11.405
I don't know that there's one
aboard this flight.

17:11.488 --> 17:13.281
Uh, there is.

17:13.365 --> 17:15.284
{\an4}Okay?

17:13.365 --> 17:15.284
You know that?

17:15.367 --> 17:17.661
{\an5}Yeah. I do.

17:15.367 --> 17:17.661
{\an3}Okay.

17:17.744 --> 17:19.663
Mr. Sanderson, I don't know

17:19.747 --> 17:21.665
that there's an air marshal
aboard this flight.

17:21.749 --> 17:23.959
They don't notify the captain of
the presence of an air marshal.

17:24.041 --> 17:25.669
They definitely don't tell
the flight attendants.

17:26.878 --> 17:28.797
Okay, yeah, no, I get it.

17:28.881 --> 17:29.965
{\an1}I get it.

17:30.048 --> 17:31.008
You get it?

17:31.091 --> 17:33.135
I get it. Thank you.

17:33.218 --> 17:35.137
Could you do me a huge favor
and just-just sit?

17:35.220 --> 17:36.513
Yeah.

17:36.597 --> 17:38.265
Yeah. Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Thank you.

17:38.348 --> 17:39.767
Okay.

17:44.772 --> 17:46.315
{\an1}Hi.

17:46.398 --> 17:49.109
{\an3}Hi.

17:49.193 --> 17:52.112
{\an1}(chuckles)
Mr. Popular.

17:52.196 --> 17:53.781
{\an3}Look, I know you
said you're a pilot.

17:53.864 --> 17:55.199
{\an1}Mm-hmm.

17:55.282 --> 17:56.742
{\an3}But you're an air
marshal, aren't you?

17:56.825 --> 17:59.328
Told you, I'm a pilot.

18:01.079 --> 18:02.873
{\an3}(sighs)

18:02.956 --> 18:05.793
{\an3}Listen, I'm an investigative
reporter, okay?

18:05.876 --> 18:08.378
{\an3}And I can be pretty sure
that an air marshal

18:08.462 --> 18:11.673
{\an3}is gonna look a lot like
a marshal in the air.

18:11.757 --> 18:13.133
{\an1}No.

18:13.217 --> 18:14.301
{\an1}(laughs):
I'm not an air marshal.

18:14.384 --> 18:15.844
{\an1}What-what do you want me
to tell you?

18:15.928 --> 18:17.513
I don't know.

18:15.928 --> 18:17.513
{\an1}Uh, I'm...

18:17.596 --> 18:20.182
{\an1}sorry to disappoint you,
brother; I'm just a pilot.

18:20.265 --> 18:24.186
{\an1}But I know air marshals,
and I know their job, Justin,

18:24.269 --> 18:26.522
{\an1}is to think
like a terrorist.

18:26.605 --> 18:30.067
{\an1}Now, the best way
to spot deceptive behavior...

18:31.944 --> 18:33.987
{\an1}...act like
a deceptive person.

18:38.450 --> 18:39.993
(sighs softly)

18:40.953 --> 18:42.996
♪ ♪

18:57.970 --> 19:00.013
♪ ♪

19:19.116 --> 19:21.869
♪ ♪

19:32.004 --> 19:34.965
MAN (whispers):
What's he doing?

19:40.846 --> 19:42.347
(people gasping)

19:42.431 --> 19:43.390
(speaks Russian)

19:43.473 --> 19:44.766
I apologize, Mr. Orlov.

19:44.850 --> 19:46.143
My name is not Orlov.

19:46.226 --> 19:47.519
{\an4}JUSTIN:
Okay, of course not,
of course not.

19:47.603 --> 19:49.897
{\an5}Get the fuck out of here!

19:47.603 --> 19:49.897
Okay, okay.

19:49.980 --> 19:52.107
{\an4}JUSTIN:
Listen, I know
you have many enemies

19:52.190 --> 19:54.067
{\an3}who will go to great
lengths to destroy you.

19:54.151 --> 19:55.944
You with Spartak Moscow?

19:56.028 --> 19:58.447
Spartak. That is
a Saint Petersburg crime family?

19:58.530 --> 20:00.616
{\an3}Russian Premier League.
We play for Grozny.

20:00.699 --> 20:03.827
We're playing a friendly game
against Spartak in Tel Aviv.

20:03.911 --> 20:05.787
{\an5}Yeah, fuck Moscow.

20:03.911 --> 20:05.787
{\an3}Fuck Moscow,
that's right. Yeah.

20:05.871 --> 20:07.956
{\an6}Mr. Sanderson-- Sir, I'm
gonna need you to sit down
and back away, please.

20:08.040 --> 20:09.583
{\an3}Mr. Sanderson,
are you kidding me?

20:09.666 --> 20:11.501
This Russian soccer league thing
is total bullshit.

20:11.585 --> 20:13.503
{\an6}What are you talking about?
Mr. Sanderson...

20:11.585 --> 20:13.503
This guy, one of them

20:13.587 --> 20:15.005
{\an5}is Igor Orlov, all right?

20:13.587 --> 20:15.005
Listen. Listen to me.

20:15.088 --> 20:16.131
{\an6}TAMMY:
I've alerted the captain
to your behavior.

20:16.214 --> 20:18.175
{\an5}You need to check their I.D.s.

20:16.214 --> 20:18.175
Don't worry about it.

20:18.258 --> 20:20.969
The Russian mafia
wants to kill Igor Orlov.

20:21.053 --> 20:22.679
Okay? They want...

20:22.763 --> 20:25.265
(shouting in Russian)

20:25.349 --> 20:27.142
(passengers and crew clamoring)

20:27.225 --> 20:28.477
{\an3}NICK:
Calm down.

20:28.560 --> 20:29.686
Jesus Christ.

20:29.770 --> 20:31.355
{\an3}DONNER:
Sit down, Mr. Orlov.

20:31.438 --> 20:32.606
Sit down! Everybody.

20:32.689 --> 20:34.274
{\an4}Calm down.

20:32.689 --> 20:34.274
(clamoring quiets)

20:34.358 --> 20:35.275
Sit down, please.

20:35.359 --> 20:37.819
{\an3}Sit down.

20:37.903 --> 20:40.322
{\an4}Thank you.

20:37.903 --> 20:40.322
Yes, sir. Excuse me.

20:40.405 --> 20:41.657
{\an3}Right here.

20:43.450 --> 20:45.202
You are threatening the safety
of these passengers.

20:45.285 --> 20:46.453
{\an3}<i>I'm</i> threatening
the safety?

20:46.536 --> 20:49.498
Now, listen. I'm warning you.

20:49.581 --> 20:51.375
Return to your seat.

20:51.458 --> 20:55.504
{\an3}Okay. I... If I were you,
I would check those guys' I.D.s,

20:55.587 --> 20:57.005
{\an3}I would check
their bags, okay?

20:57.089 --> 20:58.674
All right, I...

20:58.757 --> 21:00.801
(passengers murmuring)

21:05.097 --> 21:07.099
{\an3}(quietly):
Okay.

21:10.227 --> 21:12.980
Hi, folks.
Sorry for the disturbance.

21:13.063 --> 21:16.066
Sit back and enjoy
yourselves, okay?

21:16.149 --> 21:17.901
Thank you.

21:26.952 --> 21:30.372
{\an5}RODMAN:
The last person of interest
is an investigative reporter

21:30.455 --> 21:33.542
{\an5}directly linked to the events
of the flight:

21:33.625 --> 21:35.669
Justin Sanderson.

21:43.802 --> 21:46.430
{\an5}RODMAN:
If you've only heard one thing
about Flight 1015,

21:46.513 --> 21:48.890
{\an5}it's probably the passenger
Justin Sanderson.

21:48.974 --> 21:50.726
{\an5}NICK (over intercom):
Sir, return to your seat.

21:50.809 --> 21:52.728
{\an5}RODMAN:
Video of the investigative
journalist

21:52.811 --> 21:55.564
{\an5}causing a disturbance
on that flight

21:55.647 --> 21:58.817
{\an5}was uploaded online moments
before the plane disappeared.

21:58.900 --> 22:00.861
Here's a clip.

22:00.944 --> 22:02.404
{\an5}JUSTIN:
Check their I.D.s right now.

22:02.487 --> 22:04.823
{\an5}The Russian mafia wants
to kill Igor Orlov.

22:04.906 --> 22:06.241
{\an5}TAMMY: Pardon me?

22:04.906 --> 22:06.241
JUSTIN: Okay? They want to...

22:06.324 --> 22:07.784
(Igor shouting in Russian)

22:07.868 --> 22:10.037
{\an5}NICK:
Sir, sit down. Sir...

22:10.120 --> 22:12.247
Sir, I'm gonna need you
to take your seat, please.

22:12.330 --> 22:14.374
{\an5}RODMAN:
We can't say for certain
if this relates

22:14.458 --> 22:17.919
{\an5}to the pilot's ominous send-off,
"Good night, New York."

22:18.003 --> 22:19.880
{\an4}DONNER: I'm gonna
need you to sit down.

22:18.003 --> 22:19.880
I can't do that.

22:19.963 --> 22:20.964
Now.

22:21.048 --> 22:22.883
{\an5}Let's go. Back.

22:21.048 --> 22:22.883
Okay. All right.

22:22.966 --> 22:24.593
{\an1}DONNER:
Mr. Sanderson.

22:24.676 --> 22:25.927
{\an1}I think you're having
a psychotic break.

22:26.011 --> 22:27.554
Just wait a second.

22:27.637 --> 22:31.600
Correct me if I'm wrong,
but in about 14 minutes,

22:31.683 --> 22:35.604
you will say the words,
"Good night, New York."

22:35.687 --> 22:38.607
{\an3}Don't do it.
Do not say it.

22:41.985 --> 22:44.071
Why?

22:44.154 --> 22:45.781
Because those are the last words

22:45.864 --> 22:47.783
anyone will ever hear
from this plane.

22:47.866 --> 22:49.409
If you threaten my plane
one more time,

22:49.493 --> 22:50.535
{\an5}I swear to God...

22:49.493 --> 22:50.535
Listen to me...

22:55.082 --> 22:57.459
{\an4}ALYSHA:
Mr. Sanderson,
I'm placing you under arrest.

22:57.542 --> 22:59.002
You're the air marshal?

22:59.086 --> 23:00.420
You're being restrained
because of your threats

23:00.504 --> 23:01.713
against this aircraft.

23:05.384 --> 23:07.427
(thunder rumbling)

23:10.013 --> 23:12.015
♪ ♪

23:30.242 --> 23:32.994
{\an4}ALYSHA:
I heard it.
I don't know what you're up to,

23:33.078 --> 23:34.996
but podcasts don't
predict the future.

23:35.080 --> 23:37.958
Sorry, Justin.

23:38.041 --> 23:40.710
We're not gonna disappear.

23:42.921 --> 23:45.340
But we'll have people
waiting for you

23:45.423 --> 23:47.509
when we land that can help you.

23:47.592 --> 23:49.636
Look...

23:53.431 --> 23:55.809
...I've had a mental breakdown
before. Okay?

23:55.892 --> 23:58.061
I know what it feels like,
I know what it is,

23:58.145 --> 24:00.021
and this isn't it.

24:00.105 --> 24:02.232
{\an3}This feels
different, okay?

24:02.315 --> 24:05.068
I am not caught up
in the past here.

24:05.152 --> 24:09.531
This is now, this is real,
and I have evidence to prove

24:09.614 --> 24:11.992
that I know
what's going on here.

24:13.618 --> 24:17.205
Justin, being wrong
is an easier scenario

24:17.289 --> 24:21.209
for you to wrap your head around
because it's reality,

24:21.293 --> 24:23.712
and it's one
you can recover from.

24:26.673 --> 24:29.426
{\an4}I'm sorry, we have
a situation.

24:26.673 --> 24:29.426
Okay.

24:31.178 --> 24:32.554
(sighs)

24:35.849 --> 24:38.518
Captain, what's
the situation?

24:43.982 --> 24:46.526
(both talking quietly)

24:53.200 --> 24:55.410
{\an5}RODMAN:
The mystery of Flight 1015

24:55.493 --> 24:57.412
endures in our imagination

24:57.495 --> 25:00.624
{\an5}because we have so many pieces
of the puzzle,

25:00.707 --> 25:03.877
{\an5}yet are left
with no definite answer.

25:03.960 --> 25:08.548
{\an5}With minutes left until it would
vanish from radar at 11:15 p.m.,

25:08.632 --> 25:10.926
it seems the passengers and crew

25:11.009 --> 25:14.429
{\an5}were completely unaware
of what would happen next.

25:14.512 --> 25:16.806
{\an5}The plane was
threading a needle,

25:16.890 --> 25:19.267
{\an5}perilously close
to a thunderstorm,

25:19.351 --> 25:21.770
{\an5}carrying a unique set
of passengers

25:21.853 --> 25:24.356
for an unknown destination.

25:24.439 --> 25:27.651
{\an5}There's really only
one question left:

25:27.734 --> 25:31.154
{\an5}Could anything have been done
to prevent the tragedy?

25:31.238 --> 25:33.240
(sighs, sniffs)

25:33.323 --> 25:34.616
Hey, buddy.

25:34.699 --> 25:36.660
Hey.

25:36.743 --> 25:38.787
I believe you.

25:43.917 --> 25:45.794
I believe the shit
you're saying.

25:45.877 --> 25:48.797
You do? Why?

25:48.880 --> 25:51.800
{\an1}Because I'm a pilot.
I live in the sky.

25:51.883 --> 25:53.468
And right now
we're up 30,000 feet

25:53.551 --> 25:55.011
where no human
was ever meant to be,

25:55.095 --> 25:56.805
but we don't think about that
anymore, do we?

25:56.888 --> 25:59.641
{\an5}No.

25:56.888 --> 25:59.641
Just the fact

25:59.724 --> 26:01.434
that we're in this plane
means anything's possible.

26:01.518 --> 26:02.686
That's right.

26:02.769 --> 26:05.772
That's right. Thank you.

26:05.855 --> 26:07.857
Thanks, Joe. Thanks for...
thanks for believing me.

26:07.941 --> 26:09.484
Look, Justin,

26:09.567 --> 26:11.027
magic exists where
we're not supposed to be.

26:11.111 --> 26:12.153
{\an3}Yes.

26:12.237 --> 26:14.406
I know I'm right. I can feel it.

26:15.865 --> 26:17.826
(quiet chatter continues)

26:17.909 --> 26:20.412
Wait a second.

26:20.495 --> 26:22.831
{\an3}Joe?

26:22.914 --> 26:24.291
Yeah.

26:24.374 --> 26:27.168
You're a pilot.

26:27.252 --> 26:28.837
Yeah.

26:28.920 --> 26:31.006
{\an3}I mean, you've flown
a plane like this before.

26:31.089 --> 26:32.966
Northern Gold Star 765.

26:36.052 --> 26:38.263
{\an3}You can land
this plane safely.

26:38.346 --> 26:41.850
You can turn us around and
land us in Canada safely,

26:41.933 --> 26:44.686
{\an5}before we vanish.

26:41.933 --> 26:44.686
I-I can't get in there.

26:44.769 --> 26:46.354
Before takeoff,
every flight crew is issued

26:46.438 --> 26:47.397
an override code
to that keypad

26:47.480 --> 26:50.066
to get in the flight deck.
I don't know that code.

26:52.110 --> 26:54.904
(thunder rumbling softly)

26:58.450 --> 26:59.868
JUSTIN:
I know it.

27:00.952 --> 27:02.871
It's 1015.

27:02.954 --> 27:04.914
Did your podcast
tell you that, too?

27:06.791 --> 27:07.876
Yes.

27:07.959 --> 27:09.878
That's the answer.

27:10.962 --> 27:13.590
When I get in there, I'm gonna
drop the cabin pressure

27:13.673 --> 27:15.884
and raise the temperature.
I'm gonna put everyone to sleep.

27:15.967 --> 27:17.844
We don't want a panic situation
on our hands.

27:17.927 --> 27:19.846
{\an3}Well, won't the
oxygen masks drop down?

27:19.929 --> 27:21.890
{\an1}Yeah, sure, but I can
handle that from in there.

27:21.973 --> 27:24.392
It's perfect. They'll be
putting their masks on;

27:24.476 --> 27:25.894
they won't realize
there's no oxygen flowing.

27:25.977 --> 27:27.896
{\an1}They'll be
fast asleep.

27:34.486 --> 27:36.154
(clears throat)

27:38.865 --> 27:42.369
You're gonna need this.
Hide it.

27:42.452 --> 27:43.870
When the coast is clear,

27:43.953 --> 27:46.414
I'll give you a signal.
You'll come and join me.

27:46.498 --> 27:48.750
{\an1}Listen to me.
You're doing a good thing.

27:48.833 --> 27:51.711
You are saving these souls.

27:54.339 --> 27:56.341
♪ ♪

28:15.568 --> 28:17.195
(keypad beeps, lock clicks)

28:21.366 --> 28:23.410
(passengers murmuring)

28:24.869 --> 28:26.913
(panicked chatter)

28:29.207 --> 28:32.460
(passengers gasping,
panicked chatter continues)

28:32.544 --> 28:33.837
WOMAN:
Anybody know?

28:33.920 --> 28:36.297
MAN:
Who is this guy?

28:36.381 --> 28:37.757
(electronic chime)

28:37.841 --> 28:39.175
{\an5}JOE (over intercom):
Greetings, passengers.

28:39.259 --> 28:40.635
Oh, my God!

28:40.718 --> 28:43.012
{\an5}A little welcome
from the flight deck.

28:43.096 --> 28:45.682
{\an5}This is your new pilot,
Captain Beaumont.

28:47.684 --> 28:49.436
The, uh, former flight crew...

28:49.519 --> 28:51.813
What the fuck?

28:51.896 --> 28:54.816
{\an5}Well, they've been
incapacitated.

28:54.899 --> 28:56.651
So allow me...

28:56.734 --> 28:59.612
{\an5}allow me to wish you all
the very best for the remainder

28:59.696 --> 29:01.281
{\an5}of Northern Gold Star
Flight 1015.

28:59.696 --> 29:01.281
{\an3}Now, go.

29:01.364 --> 29:02.824
{\an1}TAMMY: Everybody,
I need you to sit down.

29:02.907 --> 29:06.119
Sit down and stay calm.
All right? Please, stay calm.

29:06.202 --> 29:07.829
{\an3}Coming through, coming through,
coming through!

29:07.912 --> 29:09.956
(passengers clamoring)

29:13.042 --> 29:15.044
(banging on door)

29:18.256 --> 29:20.758
Time for everyone...

29:23.094 --> 29:25.096
...to relax.

29:31.895 --> 29:34.063
(audio continues distorted,
chatter quiets)

29:37.901 --> 29:39.903
♪ ♪

29:42.780 --> 29:45.783
(heavy filtered breathing)

29:53.458 --> 29:55.460
(alarm beeping)

29:57.462 --> 29:58.671
(electronic chime)

29:58.755 --> 30:01.049
{\an5}JOE:
I want to thank you, Justin.

30:01.132 --> 30:02.926
You taught me something.

30:03.009 --> 30:05.386
The past is the past.

30:05.470 --> 30:07.388
And I can't get that back.

30:07.472 --> 30:09.390
{\an5}I'll never be
the man I once was,

30:09.474 --> 30:12.393
{\an5}but you've given me
the clarity of awareness

30:12.477 --> 30:15.063
{\an5}and the opportunity
to find peace

30:15.146 --> 30:18.358
{\an5}and escape the past
the only way possible.

30:20.652 --> 30:22.403
And you will, too.

30:22.487 --> 30:24.113
{\an5}WOMAN (over radio):
NGS 1015,

30:24.197 --> 30:27.867
{\an5}this is Gander Oceanic Control.
You are clear for transfer.

30:27.951 --> 30:29.577
Copy that.

30:29.661 --> 30:31.996
(thunder rumbling)

30:32.080 --> 30:34.040
Good night, New York.

30:34.123 --> 30:37.210
♪ Fly me to the moon ♪

30:37.293 --> 30:39.420
♪ Let me play among the stars ♪

30:39.504 --> 30:42.090
{\an1}Oh, shit.
He's the pilot.

30:42.173 --> 30:45.593
♪ And let me see
what spring is like ♪

30:45.677 --> 30:49.973
♪ On a-Jupiter and Mars ♪

30:50.056 --> 30:53.059
♪ In other words ♪

30:53.142 --> 30:56.854
♪ Hold my hand ♪

30:58.398 --> 31:01.109
♪ In other words ♪

31:01.192 --> 31:03.903
♪ Baby, kiss me ♪

31:06.364 --> 31:09.075
♪ Fill my heart with song ♪

31:09.158 --> 31:11.244
♪ And let me sing ♪

31:11.327 --> 31:14.289
♪ Forevermore ♪

31:14.372 --> 31:17.917
♪ You are all I long for ♪

31:18.001 --> 31:21.296
(distorted):
♪ All I worship and adore... ♪

31:21.379 --> 31:23.381
(song fades, thunder rumbling)

31:55.747 --> 31:57.123
(gasps)

31:57.206 --> 31:59.208
(panting)

32:04.088 --> 32:06.132
I'm here.

32:11.387 --> 32:13.306
I was right.

32:13.389 --> 32:15.391
(panting)

32:23.066 --> 32:24.984
(grunting)

32:25.068 --> 32:27.070
(panting)

32:30.406 --> 32:32.408
{\an5}RODMAN:
"The Mystery of Flight 1015,

32:32.492 --> 32:35.870
Part Two: The End of Civility."

32:35.953 --> 32:38.373
{\an5}The first installment
in this bizarre story

32:38.456 --> 32:41.000
{\an5}was our most popular
podcast to date.

32:41.084 --> 32:42.877
And when we last left you,

32:42.960 --> 32:46.172
{\an5}we thought we had told the tale
of an unexplained mystery

32:46.255 --> 32:49.509
{\an5}so bizarre it would be left
to historians to unravel.

32:49.592 --> 32:53.262
{\an8}Rescuers spent months
after the plane's disappearance

32:53.346 --> 32:54.931
{\an8}looking for debris,

32:55.014 --> 32:58.017
{\an8}hoping to find signs
of survivors.

32:58.101 --> 33:00.353
{\an8}The search would
go on for months,

33:00.436 --> 33:02.438
{\an8}but to no avail.

33:02.522 --> 33:07.402
{\an8}Until a cargo ship happened
upon a near-barren atoll.

33:07.485 --> 33:09.237
{\an8}And incredibly,

33:09.320 --> 33:13.074
{\an8}every passenger
from Flight 1015 had survived,

33:13.157 --> 33:14.534
{\an8}except one.

33:14.617 --> 33:16.577
{\an8}None of the survivors
could explain it,

33:16.661 --> 33:18.538
{\an8}but Justin Sanderson
was missing,

33:18.621 --> 33:22.417
{\an8}his whereabouts,
still to this day, unknown.

33:30.425 --> 33:32.260
Hey, buddy.

33:32.343 --> 33:33.970
{\an1}Hey.

33:34.053 --> 33:36.097
Hey, where you going?

33:38.307 --> 33:41.060
(quiet murmuring)

33:46.649 --> 33:48.568
That's him.
Is that him?

33:48.651 --> 33:50.445
Hey, I tried to save us.

33:50.528 --> 33:54.198
(angry murmuring)

33:56.659 --> 33:58.453
Justin, you did this.

33:58.536 --> 34:01.330
How could you do this?

34:01.414 --> 34:03.458
What did you people do, huh?!
Nothing!

34:05.918 --> 34:07.920
What did you do?!
Get away from me!

34:08.880 --> 34:09.630
Get away!

34:09.714 --> 34:12.091
{\an5}How could you do this, asshole?!

34:09.714 --> 34:12.091
No! No!

34:12.175 --> 34:14.552
(angry clamoring)

34:17.179 --> 34:19.098
(clamoring fades)

34:19.181 --> 34:22.018
In his final moments,
Justin Sanderson made the case

34:22.101 --> 34:24.937
that he did everything he could
to avert disaster.

34:25.021 --> 34:27.648
But in the end,
he was an investigative reporter

34:27.732 --> 34:30.109
unwilling to
investigate himself,

34:30.193 --> 34:32.152
until it was too late.

34:32.235 --> 34:34.322
Justin discovered
that the flight path to hell

34:34.405 --> 34:36.491
is paved with good intentions,

34:36.574 --> 34:39.994
and it passes directly...

34:40.077 --> 34:42.121
through The Twilight Zone.

